@hotp_nk They won’t receive the rest of the chain; after being moved to BCC they won’t get any further emails. The BCC is just so they know you’re working on it and they can check it off their list.

By the way, this is the little stuff that trips people up when they’re trying to break into tech. 

Not hard to learn, but there are 100 subtle games you’re supposed to know how to play that no one teaches you.

Then when you learn them it becomes obvious/second nature.

And apparently lots of folks don’t know what you’re supposed to do.

Answer: Move the person you were emailing with to BCC, say something like, “Thanks, [name], moving you to BCC.”

Then work on scheduling and logistics with the assistant.

@EverestBrady Move them to BCC, say something like, “Thanks, [name], moving you to BCC.”

Then work on scheduling and logistics with the assistant.

Has anyone written up a good guide on advanced email etiquette?

In most industries it’s so wound into licensing and accreditation that students are looking at 6-8 years of college as the only way to get the 1-3 years of necessary job training. https://t.co/ll4V9GRrBu

text: When vocational training in high schools generally failed, instead of dividing the university system and vocational in two, colleges and universities flexed their political muscle to effectively push vocational training for white collar jobs to *after* the university by law. https://t.co/qa0J4px7I9

Meanwhile, the university system considered itself largely a finishing school for the elite and wealthy leaders of society, and not a fit for job preparation, especially for blue collar jobs. https://t.co/Udz86FxqLL

A short history or job training in the United States:

We used to have apprenticeships for most every trade, but after the industrial revolution unions and business leaders made a kind of compromise. Result:

Eliminate apprenticeships and put vocational training in High Schools. https://t.co/15ohc0c2og
@readomain In my ideal world students would see themselves as apprentices and we would pay them accordingly. So yes.
@Socialism_Bad I don’t believe we’ve used metrics that are deceptive whatsoever.

These 3 things will likely never change; we’ll be working on them until the end of time, but I expect giant strides to be made in 1 & 2.

More soon, and soooo much work to do!

3. Increasing accessibility and availability.

This can only come after the first two steps, but we want Lambda School to be more accessible to the folks who are unable (or stretched) to take part right now.

2. Increasing the smoothness of the Lambda School experience

Succeeding at Lambda  is *hard*, and we’re working on rooting out and eliminating any unnecessary obstacle to that.

A lot of unsexy, behind the scenes refinement that make a huge difference to student experience.

Three things we’re working on at Lambda School in 2021:

1. Increasing the surety of a great outcome.

This is where I’m spending the vast majority of my time right now. 

The closer we can get to every student walking into a great job automatically the better off we all are.

text: @willwearing Ah we removed some things, but have much better objective measures now
@willwearing What changes?

It’s not enough to say, “x isn’t a good measure.” You have to replace x with something that is better.

Right now we’re just getting rid of all the measures we have in education and that doesn’t end well.

We’re about to watch this play out with the removal of the SAT in many universities.

The SAT is a suboptimal measure in many ways, especially among underrepresented groups.

But it’s about to be replaced with additional focus on grades and extracurriculars. Which are way worse.

urls.title: It’s time to abolish the college GPA

Everyone knows what the main branch is, everyone knows what’s production and what’s sandbox, everyone can see the changes made historically, etc.

Think about how difficult it would be for that to happen without git/version control.
@cyberrose81 Public lands

Think about your standard git flow:

Branch, commit, pull request, discuss/review, deploy, test, merge.

Most every company uses a similar flow by default, and it’s... shockingly elegant and reliable

For all of its flaws, software has very well-defined methodologies for how it can be changed, who makes the changes, who reviews them, areas for staging vs production, rigorous testing, etc.

Not many non-software organizations have such robust protocols.

Important to note that we see Fellows as an extension of the educational experience. 

We designed Fellows as a way to make Lambda’s student journey stronger and more realistic. Our “Labs” program is already a simulation; this is just like Labs, but at an external company.
In most cases we can get a Fellow submitting their first meaningful pull request within 24 hours.

The pushback we had initially was always "Well it takes us more than a month to spin up a software engineer and get them productive.

If that's the case there's something broken either with the training the engineer has or with the onboarding process, usually both.

One thing that we're realizing with Lambda Fellows is that is that most companies actually have no clue how onboard software engineers well.

One of the biggest benefits to companies of Lambda Fellows comes is that run that playbook for you.
RT @avnerbraverman: We're happy and proud to be beta users of this program. Yet to meet a non-awesome @LambdaSchool grad https://t.co/4TuEo…

She never made much from weddings because she never charged enough and was always throwing them at cost for folks who couldn’t afford much. You could throw a fully catered and decorated wedding in her backyard for ~$500.

Beyond the first unit the amount owed grows gradually (both upfront tuition and the ISA).

So if you attend Lambda School for two months full-time, pass unit 2, and withdraw, you only owe 15% of tuition.

First: If don't successfully complete a full unit (a unit is one month in full-time, two months in part-time) you don't pay for that unit.

So you can attend Lambda School for a full unit (1 month full-time, 2 months part-time), and if you decide to withdraw you pay $0

Lambda School is making our very forgiving refund policy *even more* forgiving.

You already only pay tuition if you get a high-paying job. 

Now, in the unlikely scenario you decide to withdraw early *and then* get a job, we're making the tuition commitment tiny.

urls.title: Air Filters, Pollution and Student Achievement
urls.description: This paper identifies the achievement impact of installing air filters in classrooms for the first time. To do so, I leverage a unique setting arising from the largest gas leak in United States history, whereby the offending gas company installed air filters in every classroom, office and common area for all schools within five miles of the leak (but not beyond). This variation allows me to compare student achievement in schools receiving air filters relative to those that did not using a spatial regression discontinuity design.

urls.description: Aisle upon aisle of fresh produce, cheap meat, and sugary cereal — a delicious embodiment of free-market capitalism, right? Not quite. The supermarket was in fact the endpoint of the U.S. government’s battle for agricultural abundance against the U.S.S.R. Our farm policies were built to dominate, not necessarily to nourish — and we are still living with the consequences.

In the 1920s chicken was pound for pound as expensive as lobster.

That's literally an ISA built with debt.

Now look at me in the eye and tell me the loan with no interest that goes away after a few years no matter what is "indentured servitude" and your student loan is not.

Give me a break.

There's a part of me that wants to create a product that actually *is* a loan that mimics ISA terms entirely.

Imagine a loan with:

* 0% interest
* Only make payments if you have a high income
* Forgiven once you've made 24 payments
* Forgiven after 5-7 years no matter what

@RwoltX in that instance it's just a way better zero interest loan where you only have to make payments if you have a high income.

still dramatically better than status quo.

And people say "ISAs are indentured servitude." 🙄

Every. Single. Time. I've researched who is saying that line it ends up being someone who is incentivized for there to be more student loans.

This is one thing people don't understand about why income share agreements are so much better than student loans.

No interest. The amount you owe does not grow.

Compare that to someone who took out $75k in loans, has paid $120k over 10 years, and owes... $75k.

Most note-taking apps force you to think in an organized manner like a computer would, and that friction stops your thinking process.

Roam Research lets you do your thing as a human and self-organizes your thoughts in the background. https://t.co/EfripXmyA4
@chrismaddern @StephanSturges I’m confident enough in the product and (more importantly) the people behind it that the savings is worth it

@NickADobos Ya and second monitor, office chair, etc.

You spend about 20x as much time in those vs your car.

Now the tricky part about your consumer-facing productivity app is you have to actually be an enormous productivity boost to be worth paying a substantial amount for.

Most just aren’t there.

If the apps save... maybe half an hour a month they’re probably worth it.

They probably save more than an hour a day.

People seem surprised when you pay $30/month for email (Superhuman), $8/month for a note taking/second brain app (Roam Research), etc.

There are 160 working hours in a month (for me much more), so it costs about 25 cents an hour for two enormous productivity boosts.
